00:43:07.250 --> 00:43:15.460
&gt;&gt;audience #1: OK, so I was interested in
your discussion of the feature wars in the

00:43:15.460 --> 00:43:18.250
early days of printing with moveable type.

00:43:18.250 --> 00:43:22.769
Can you tell us about any innovative features
introduced in that time that didn't work out

00:43:22.769 --> 00:43:24.339
and that we don't remember today?

00:43:24.339 --> 00:43:33.910
&gt;&gt;Steven: Oh, that's a really good question.
That's a great way of approaching-- I'm trying

00:43:33.910 --> 00:43:42.130
to think if there's anything that jumps to
mind. One of the things I'm really interested

00:43:42.130 --> 00:43:49.950
in terms of the history of ideas is that kind
of reverse history, where we tend to tell

00:43:49.950 --> 00:43:56.540
the history of the winners. And it's just
as important, I think, to look at two different

00:43:56.540 --> 00:44:00.299
kinds of losers. I'm gonna give a theoretical
answer because I can't think of a good concrete

00:44:00.299 --> 00:44:06.380
example. There are two different kinds of
losers that are worth studying. The first

00:44:06.380 --> 00:44:12.640
is, the good idea that failed, right? So,
in the book, one of the things I talk about,

00:44:12.640 --> 00:44:16.650
I'm sure this is familiar to most people in
this audience; one of the most fascinating

00:44:16.650 --> 00:44:20.950
stories in the history of technology was Charles
Babbage. And basically, inventing the computer,

00:44:20.950 --> 00:44:28.160
the digital computer in the middle of the
19th century, with Ada Lovelace, the first

00:44:28.160 --> 00:44:35.300
programmer; Lord Byron's daughter, helping
him. It's such a cool story because he was

00:44:35.300 --> 00:44:40.260
literally a hundred years ahead of his time,
which almost never happens, right? It's amazing

00:44:40.260 --> 00:44:47.269
how reliably ideas come at the right time;
people really jump a hundred years ahead.

00:44:47.269 --> 00:44:52.779
And what Babbage was trying to do was build
a programmable computer with steam industrial

00:44:52.779 --> 00:44:56.140
era parts. He was trying to build a steam-powered
programmable computer and you just couldn't

00:44:56.140 --> 00:45:02.619
do it, right? So, that's one way in which--
his idea, as visionary as it was, it was so

00:45:02.619 --> 00:45:06.380
far ahead of its time, it died out and most
of the principles had to be rediscovered a

00:45:06.380 --> 00:45:10.621
hundred years later when people started actually
to build computers with vacuum tubes and so

00:45:10.621 --> 00:45:14.580
on. So, there are ideas that fail because
they are good, but they're just ahead of their

00:45:14.580 --> 00:45:21.490
time in some kind of way. The other question
is ideas that in a sense are bad ideas that

00:45:21.490 --> 00:45:25.819
stick around for too long. This is a big thing
that I think intellectuals historians should

00:45:25.819 --> 00:45:32.720
spend more time on; the history of being wrong.
Because no doubt, we're all walking around

00:45:32.720 --> 00:45:38.990
with our own biases or misunderstandings of
the world that 30 years from now, or a hundred

00:45:38.990 --> 00:45:43.779
years from now, we're gonna go, "How were
we so stupid?" Right? And trying to figure

00:45:43.779 --> 00:45:47.750
out how those ideas have historically stayed
in place for such a long time. In the "Ghost

00:45:47.750 --> 00:45:52.030
Map", the theory of the Miasma theory, the
cholera being in the air is one of those.

00:45:52.030 --> 00:45:55.010
Like, why did it stick around for as long
as it did? I think it's a really interesting

00:45:55.010 --> 00:45:59.599
kind of problem. So, to totally fail to answer
your question, but hopefully say something

00:45:59.599 --> 00:46:04.380
interesting, I think that going back and looking
at innovations that failed, either because

00:46:04.380 --> 00:46:12.200
they were wrong or poorly designed, but interesting.
Or innovations that were so good that people

00:46:12.200 --> 00:46:16.299
couldn't deal with them yet on some level.
That's a really fertile field of discovery.

00:46:16.299 --> 00:46:17.779
Go ahead.

00:46:17.779 --> 00:46:23.670
&gt;&gt;audience #2: I'd be interested in your take
on a classic question from the history of

00:46:23.670 --> 00:46:26.730
technology, which is, are innovations inevitable?

00:46:26.730 --> 00:46:31.569
Or, meaning, could ideas come together by
someone who just puts them together in the

00:46:31.569 --> 00:46:35.390
right way or is it a matter of genius, or
a matter of an individual’s contribution

00:46:35.390 --> 00:46:39.720
seeing things that maybe are apparent to others,
but who they fail to put together?

00:46:39.720 --> 00:46:43.109
&gt;&gt;Steven: Yeah. It's a great question. By
the way, another fantastic book that deals

00:46:43.109 --> 00:46:47.000
with this and maybe a little bit more, although
I talk about this is Kevin Kelley's book,

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:50.269
"What Technology Wants". I'm sure Kevin has
been here, or is coming here yet.

00:46:50.269 --> 00:46:51.269
[laughter]

00:46:51.269 --> 00:46:53.760
Two weeks ago, there you go. Kevin and I,
we did a fun event near a public library,

00:46:53.760 --> 00:47:01.809
which is online, actually. And we talked about
this quite a bit. There's a term for it, which

00:47:01.809 --> 00:47:06.109
is the multiple, right? In the history of
science and technology where they're again

00:47:06.109 --> 00:47:10.880
and again, there are these multiple, independent
discoveries, or inventions, or the same basic,

00:47:10.880 --> 00:47:17.030
the same thing, happening without direct interaction
between the participants and it just, there

00:47:17.030 --> 00:47:22.769
are like, 150 of them in the canon of big
ideas that are out there and have been collected.

00:47:22.769 --> 00:47:28.820
And historically, it's been described in this
very vague zeitgeisty way. Like, something

00:47:28.820 --> 00:47:39.950
was in the air, and I think that in saying
that these ideas on some level are inevitable,

00:47:39.950 --> 00:47:44.540
that you reach a certain point and someone
will figure out how to build a personal computer,

00:47:44.540 --> 00:47:51.750
digital computer, a phone, is true. It doesn't
mean there aren't geniuses, right? This book

00:47:51.750 --> 00:47:57.040
is not against the idea that some people are,
by nature of their genes or their education

00:47:57.040 --> 00:48:02.160
and probably some mix of that; some people
are smarter than other people. So, whoever

00:48:02.160 --> 00:48:06.280
it is who gets to discover that thing in that
particular moment of time is gonna be more

00:48:06.280 --> 00:48:10.480
likely to be someone who's smart and well-educated
than someone who's not, but it's very, very

00:48:10.480 --> 00:48:15.080
hard for someone to have that insight at the
wrong time, right? It's impossible to invent

00:48:15.080 --> 00:48:19.240
a microwave oven in 1650. It just cannot be
done, right. There are just limitations on

00:48:19.240 --> 00:48:24.759
that. So, the example that's very close to
my heart is, in The Invention of Air, the

00:48:24.759 --> 00:48:29.440
hero of that book is Joseph Priestly, who
is most famous for isolating oxygen for the

00:48:29.440 --> 00:48:34.760
first time. He's known as the discoverer of
oxygen, although when he did it, he called

00:48:34.760 --> 00:48:39.099
it "dephilostigated air" instead of oxygen,
which was not a very good brand and didn't

00:48:39.099 --> 00:48:44.540
really stick. And it turned out that actually,
two other people, Lavoisier and Scheele, the

00:48:44.540 --> 00:48:52.180
Swedish, I believe, scientist, also isolated
oxygen within about a year; somewhere between

00:48:52.180 --> 00:48:57.029
1772 and 1774. Three people, more or less
independently, have isolated oxygen for the

00:48:57.029 --> 00:49:02.211
first time. So, weird, right? How did that
happen, right? But when you go back and look

00:49:02.211 --> 00:49:07.490
at it, you realize that there are a set of
supporting platforms that basically make that

00:49:07.490 --> 00:49:12.779
thought thinkable for the first time, right
around that period. And some of it is technology,

00:49:12.779 --> 00:49:17.420
right? One of the key things that they has
is they developed, in the 1750s, very accurate

00:49:17.420 --> 00:49:23.099
scales. And part of the way that they could
figure out that oxygen was something was that

00:49:23.099 --> 00:49:30.259
when you burn things, they got ever so slightly
heavier, right? Because of combustion and

00:49:30.259 --> 00:49:35.140
so, but you couldn't pick that out if you
didn't have really, really precise scales.

00:49:35.140 --> 00:49:41.759
And the other thing they had was they discovered
vacuums about a century before. And up until

00:49:41.759 --> 00:49:45.839
the discovery of a vacuum, people never thought
of the air as been something you study; it

00:49:45.839 --> 00:49:49.900
was just this empty space between things.
If you were gonna use this great, new scientific

00:49:49.900 --> 00:49:54.019
method, you wanted to study a tree or a body
or a rock, but why would you study the stuff

00:49:54.019 --> 00:49:56.900
between all those things, right? But then
they figured out that there was this thing

00:49:56.900 --> 00:50:01.829
called a vacuum, which seemed to look just
like air, but not be air. And so, it suddenly

00:50:01.829 --> 00:50:06.819
suggested this idea that there was something
between us all that we could study. So, without

00:50:06.819 --> 00:50:11.289
unlocking that as a kind of a paradigm that
you could get interested in, you couldn't

00:50:11.289 --> 00:50:18.019
even start to solve the problem. So, I think
what happens is there are these stages and

00:50:18.019 --> 00:50:22.040
the technology advances, the perspectives
advance and they unlock a whole new set of

00:50:22.040 --> 00:50:25.519
possibilities. In the book, I call this the
adjacent possible, which is a phrase from

00:50:25.519 --> 00:50:30.900
Stewart Kaufman. And then who actually explores
the adjacent possible, some of it is luck,

00:50:30.900 --> 00:50:37.769
some of it is environment, some of it is education,
some of it is skills, mental skills, curiosity,

00:50:37.769 --> 00:50:41.559
but there are many, many doors that can't
be unlocked until you get to the next level,

00:50:41.559 --> 00:50:43.809
which is suddenly sounding like a video game,
but anyway.

00:50:43.809 --> 00:50:49.900
That's the video game theory of scientific
creativity. All right. We probably have a

00:50:49.900 --> 00:50:50.900
little bit of time, yeah?

