the 19th century metropolitan novel, so I

00:51:32.200 --> 00:51:35.829
spent a lot of time on the cultural history
of London and the city. So, some of "Ghost

00:51:35.829 --> 00:51:42.549
Map" is out of that, but I always had a technology
interest. And so, when I was still in grad

00:51:42.549 --> 00:51:48.539
school, I started "Feed", the first online
magazine that had established writers writing

00:51:48.539 --> 00:51:55.170
for it. And really, in a way, that's become
a lot more common now. It built my writing

00:51:55.170 --> 00:52:00.480
career by publishing myself and my friends
at my web scene, basically. We didn't have

00:52:00.480 --> 00:52:04.970
blogs back then, we had web magazines. And
so I sold my first book, which was "Interface

00:52:04.970 --> 00:52:11.300
Culture", about technology and interfaces
on the backs of my experience with "Feed".

00:52:11.300 --> 00:52:16.660
So, it was the first generation of writers
who built a career for themselves through

00:52:16.660 --> 00:52:22.130
the self-publishing mechanism of the Web,
which is now much more commonplace. And then

00:52:22.130 --> 00:52:26.109
at a certain point after I wrote that book,
I looked at my shelf and realized the last

00:52:26.109 --> 00:52:31.440
30 book I've read were all science books and
that was just the direction my brain was going

00:52:31.440 --> 00:52:36.789
in. So, I thought, "OK, maybe I could try
and do that myself." And so, I wrote "Emergence",

00:52:36.789 --> 00:52:42.510
which is half technology, half science, half
urban theory I guess. And I loved so much

00:52:42.510 --> 00:52:46.599
this moving back and forth between different
disciplines; all the things I was talking

00:52:46.599 --> 00:52:51.650
about today. And the only other thing that's
interesting I would say about my career is

00:52:51.650 --> 00:52:57.190
that I've done these little start-ups while
writing the books. And the start-ups, in a

00:52:57.190 --> 00:53:01.540
way, are hobbies that I was talking about,
right? I think of myself primarily as an author,

00:53:01.540 --> 00:53:06.070
but I love going off and starting some new
Web thing and actually going and hanging out

00:53:06.070 --> 00:53:11.359
with human beings and talking to them and
building something together. And each start-up

00:53:11.359 --> 00:53:17.290
I've done has had a direct connection to something
that I was writing, in one way or another.

00:53:17.290 --> 00:53:22.220
And so, Outside.in, the hyper-local service,
came out of writing "Ghost Map". I was writing

00:53:22.220 --> 00:53:26.400
about communities and maps and neighborhoods
and I was reading all these local bloggers

00:53:26.400 --> 00:53:31.660
in Brooklyn where I live. And truly, I actually
owe you all a thanks for this; the Google

00:53:31.660 --> 00:53:35.410
Maps API had been released, so I was writing
about neighborhoods, communities, I was reading

00:53:35.410 --> 00:53:40.930
local bloggers and there's this new platform
of mapping that was suddenly possible. And

00:53:40.930 --> 00:53:47.109
Outside.in is the intersection of those three
vectors, basically. The best thing about it

00:53:47.109 --> 00:53:51.670
is that I've been incredibly lucky that I
basically get to write about whatever I'm

00:53:51.670 --> 00:53:56.810
interested in and sometimes my publisher is
like, "Wait, what are you writing a book about

00:53:56.810 --> 00:53:59.720
18th century chemistry? What's going on?"
But most of the time, they've let me just

00:53:59.720 --> 00:54:05.650
do these things and trusted me, which is a
great gig.

00:54:05.650 --> 00:54:08.730
All right. All right, thank you for coming
out. It's great to see you all here and I'd

00:54:08.730 --> 00:54:09.730
be happy to sign some books.

00:54:09.730 --> 00:54:09.819
[applause]

